<p>To secure the visa, applicants must <a href="https://www.ice.gov/doclib/forms/i352.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">file a Department of Homeland Security Form I-352</a> and deposit the bond amount with the US government.&nbsp;</p>



<p>The money is refunded only if the traveller leaves the US within the authorised stay period, never uses the visa before expiry, or is denied entry at a US port after arrival.</p>



<p>The US State Department said the programme is designed to <a href="https://travel.state.gov/content/travel/en/News/visas-news/countries-subject-to-visa-bonds.html" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">reduce visa overstays</a>. In reality, it creates one of the steepest financial barriers to mobility facing African travellers today.</p>



<p>An analysis of the US Department of State visa issuance data shows that 522,721 people from the 30 affected African countries received B1/B2 visas between the 2022 and 2024 fiscal years. That translates to an annual average of about 174,240 travellers.</p>



